## Commands

- `{{ package_manager }} run dev` starts the Nuxt development server.
- `{{ package_manager }} run build` builds the production app.
- `{{ package_manager }} run preview` previews the production build.
- `{{ package_manager }} run lint` runs Nuxt-aware ESLint.
- `{{ package_manager }} run typecheck` runs Nuxt TypeScript checks.
- `{{ package_manager }} run test` runs Vitest unit tests.
- `{{ package_manager }} run test:unit` is an explicit alias for unit tests.
- `{{ package_manager }} run test:e2e` {% if use_playwright %}runs Playwright E2E tests{% else %}prints a disabled message because Playwright was not selected{% endif %}.
- `{{ package_manager }} run check` runs lint, typecheck and unit tests. Run E2E separately when the browser runtime is installed.

## AI-First Workflow

Use `docs/workflow.md` as the source of truth for meaningful frontend work.

Start with product intent and user flow. Create PRDs for large product changes, define features and screen states before implementation, and read the relevant design and technical docs for the change. Implement small vertical slices that can be reviewed and tested independently.

## Folder Structure

- `app/` contains Nuxt app code using the Nuxt 4 directory structure.
- `server/api/` contains server routes.
- `tests/unit/` contains Vitest tests.
- `tests/e2e/` contains Playwright tests when enabled.
- `product/` contains product intent, user flows, screen specs, features and PRDs.
- `design/` contains UI principles, accessibility notes, design tokens and wireframes.
- `docs/` contains workflow, architecture, conventions, API contracts, testing strategy and ADRs.
- `project/` contains task sequencing, backlog and completed work notes.
- `CHANGELOG.md` records notable product and application changes.

## Design System

The project uses a minimal token-based design system:

- `design/design-tokens.md` documents colors, spacing, radius and shadows.
- `app/assets/css/tokens.css` exposes the same values as CSS variables.
- `design/ui-principles.md`, `design/typography.md` and `design/accessibility.md` define UI constraints.
- `docs/component-rules.md` explains how components should use tokens and states.
{% if use_tailwind %}
- `tailwind.config.ts` maps the same token values into the Tailwind theme.
{% endif %}

Change shared visual values in `design/design-tokens.md` and `app/assets/css/tokens.css` before using them in components. Do not invent one-off colors or spacing in Vue files.

## Development Rules

- All code comments, UI labels, component names and developer-facing names must be in English.
- Planning documents may be in Czech or English.
- Read the relevant PRD when needed, feature spec, user flow, screen spec, docs and task before implementation.
- Prefer small vertical slices over broad horizontal refactors.
- Do not start from components. Start from user flow and screen state.
- Keep pages, layouts, components, composables, stores and utilities small, focused and easy to maintain.
- Split files when they start mixing unrelated responsibilities or become difficult to scan.
- Use composables for reusable logic.
- Use stores only for shared application state.
- Avoid global state for local UI state.
- Do not put server-only logic into client code.
- All UI styling must use design tokens.
- Do not invent new colors, spacing, radius or shadows inside components.
- Every non-trivial UI must handle loading, empty and error states.
- Every task should update `project/TASK_SEQUENCE.md` if the backlog changes.
- Every implementation task should include tests when practical.
- Do not add large dependencies without an ADR.
- Update `CHANGELOG.md` for user-visible changes, notable technical changes and release preparation.

